I think that it'd be better to create three functions here: validateSubnetAlloc, and two helper functions, validateSubnetAutoAlloc & validateSubnetParamsAlloc. Then, in validateSubnetAlloc, you can do:

    if (parsedParams.subnet_alloc) {
        validateSubnetAutoAlloc(opts, original, parsedParams, callback);
    } else {
        validateSubnetParamsAlloc(opts, original, parsedParams, callback);
    }

In the two helper functions, you can then assert that each of the fields is or isn't present, and do the appropriate errors.invalidParam/errors.missingParam calls with each name, and call the callback with an array of the errors. That will allow us to create more easily understand error messages when we have conflicts.

Perhaps split this complicated expression into two separate if checks, like:

if (parsedParams.subnet &&
    (!parsedParams.provision_start_ip || !parsedParams.provision_end_ip)) {
    ERR();
}

if (parsedParams.subnet_alloc) {
    if (!parsedParams.addr_family || !parsedParams.subnet_prefix) {
        ERR();
    }
    if (!parsedParams.fabric || !parsedParams.vnet_id) {
        ERR();
    }
}

