You can just write at the beginning of the function:

    assert.number(plen, 'plen');

Which will achieve what you're doing with assert.ok and make sure that it is actually a number. You can do the same with the asserts in decrementSubnet().

You could use an object (passed to this function and passed on to listFilteredNetworksStream, either as part of opts, or a separate argument) and set a specific value on that object when you wanted to stop, e.g.:
  if (state.abort) { ... }

then could could set state.abort in the allocateSubnet function when you've found a subnet.

Maybe simplify this code - by just keeping track of the prevNetwork in the loop, for example:

    var prevNetwork = null;
    stream.on('readable', function () {
        var network = stream.read(1);
        while (network) {
            if (prevNetwork !== null) {
                walker([prevNetwork, network]);
            }
            prevNetwork = network;
            network = stream.read(1);
        }
